AB  - The Children's Commissioner has a statutory duty to promote awareness of the views and interests of children, particularly regarding their physical and mental health and emotional well-being, their education, training and recreation and protecting them from harm and neglect. This paper summarises the report resulting from the Commissioner's third visit to Yarl's Wood Immigration Removal Centre to examine the progress made in addressing concerns raised regarding children's experience of the immigration removal process and detention, which sets out the children's perspective of their experiences following any changes arising from the previous report. It covers the report's findings on the United Nations Convention on the Rights of the Child and the decision to detain, preparation for removal, the arrest process, children's concerns during detention, healthcare, safeguarding children, reviewing detention, and arrangements for pregnant and nursing mothers and their babies and infants. It concludes by reiterating the Commissioner's contention that arrest and detention are inherently damaging to children, and that Yarl's Wood is no place for a child, and summarising the key recommendations of the report
