AB  - Although numerous refugee groups reside in Australia, research into the psychological health of Greek-Cypriot refugees is nonexistent at present. Research conducted into all other refugee populations however, has concluded that refugees are more susceptible to developing mental illnesses, as a result of both premigratory (e.g., exposure to trauma) and post-migratory factors (e.g., difficult acculturation). The maladaptive events that preceded emigration by Greek-Cypriot refugees include forceful exodus, false imprisonment, and long term accommodation in concentration camps. Post-migration factors that commonly impact the quality of the acculturative process include age, the degree of family and social support available in the host country, English language proficiency, socioeconomic status, degree of perceived racism and discrimination, and the degree of incongruence between pre-migration expectations and post-migration reality. The traumata endured by many Greek-Cypriot refugees and the adverse psychological effects that are likely to have resulted require immediate investigation. Therefore, the aims of this study are (a) to measure the current psychological health of Greek-Cypriot refugees living in Australia, (b) to measure the prevalence, types, and severity of traumatic life events, and (c) to investigate the impact of family support on the psychological health of traumatised individuals. The specific hypotheses include: (a) there is a positive correlation between the degree of traumata suffered in Cyprus and the level of psychopathology currently experienced; and (b) the degree of psychopathology suffered is related to the level of family support, type of coping strategies adopted, and the quality of the acculturative experience in the host country
