AB  - The impetus for developing this monograph came from the conference, "The Refugee Convention: Where to from here?", held at the University of New South Wales (UNSW) in December 2001 under the auspice of the UNSW Refugee Research Centre, the Refugee Council of Australia, and the Australian National Council of Refugee Women. Many of the issues addressed in conference presentations were considered at the time to need urgent attention, and one avenue for raising awareness and sparking community and professional involvement was the publication and dissemination of presented material. The Transcultural Mental Health Centre (TMHC) agreed to publish a monograph encompassing those presentations that were particularly relevant to mental health issues concerning refugees and asylum seekers. We still have children languishing in detention, we still have asylum seekers and people on temporary protection visas who have no idea what their futures hold, and we still have a settlement process that is seriously flawed for many refugees who have been afforded permanent protection in this country. Chapters in this monograph draw attention to mental health implications of these situations, some arguing for changes to immigration policy to minimise the development of mental health problems in the first place and others arguing for greater sensitivity and more appropriate responses to existing mental health needs within current immigration policy. An introductory chapter provides an overview of the laws, policies, and procedures that govern Australia's response to refugees and asylum seekers. The chapters that follow are in two clusters, based on the immigration status of the particular refugee/asylum seeking communities that are the focus of concern. The first cluster of four chapters addresses the plight of those who have sought asylum in Australia without having been assessed as refugees prior to their arrival. The second cluster of chapters concerns people from war-torn backgrounds who have been granted the right to stay in Australia permanently. Collectively, this compilation of chapters contributes to the knowledge-base of mental health workers in a number of ways: it points to the importance of understanding the background of trauma from which refugees and asylum seekers come and the mental health legacy that results from these experiences; it points to the link between formal immigration status and particular sources of emotional stress that refugees and asylum seekers encounter in Australia; and it points to the long-term nature of some of the mental health implications of resettlement. Individually, the chapters each provide more specific insights into mental health issues of particular groups. Armed with the information contained within this monograph, mental health workers will be well prepared, not only to respond more appropriately to refugees and asylum seekers they encounter as clients/patients, but also to join the growing push for legislative and policy change that can promote mental health in a more positive way from the outset. [Adapted from Preface]
