AB  - This article deals with the issues linked to refugees in Australia. In the face of the refugee, and in the wake of the Tampa crisis, the Border Protection Act, the Pacific Solution, the immigration prisons, and the Danish laws, people in Australia allegedly face an impasse. Asylum seekers in Australian detention centers are depressed, frustrated, fearful, bewildered, defiant, and proud. The refugees are prisoners not only of barbed wire, armed guards and legislation. In Australia, irony and paradox are now a dangerous form of commonsense. They have been stitched into the fabric of its foreign and defense policy, and its images of nationhood and being. The Tampa crisis could not be allowed to port in Australia sovereignty, despite that sovereignty having been qualified by our signature on the 1951 Refugee Convention and 1967 Protocol, and despite the Australian government's aggressive promotion of open borders to trade and capital. National identity, survival and being in the country is based on exclusion, on repression, on a profound functional cruelty toward the lives of others. The refugee seems to be defined by homelessness, by falling between the cracks, of nations, laws, and the decks of rickety boats
