AB  - The creation of a new class of refugees granted Temporary Protection Visas may be indicative of the intent to shift from permanent resettlement of refugees towards a model of provisional safety and eventual repatriation. This new visa category appears to be having a significant impact on the mental health of the refugees. Initial evidence seems to indicate that the experiences of this client group upon arrival in Australia -- that is, being detained in detention centres, restrictions imposed by temporary visa, perceived discrimination by various agencies/services -- exacerbate symptoms of anxiety, depression, and PTSD. The resultant symptom picture could perhaps provide evidence of a more complex form of PTSD. Further research is needed to substantiate the above hypothesis and also assist the Early Health Assessment and Intervention (EHAI) program develop appropriate service delivery models to work more effectively with this client group. [Text, p. 78]
