AB  - Previous research studies and inspection reports have highlighted that the experience of detention, even for a relatively brief period of time, has a detrimental effect on the mental and physical health of children. This paper is intended to provide further evidence of these experiences on children and families. It investigates the experiences of UK immigration detention of children and their families. The study was based on the views and experiences of 32 families including 34 children who were detained with their parents and 14 children who experienced the detention of their parents while they lived in the community in the UK. The evidence was collected through family case files and qualitative interviews. Findings revealed that most of the families were already vulnerable and had sought sanctuary, refuge and asylum in the UK. The majority were detrimentally affected by a period in immigration detention and experienced deterioration in both their physical and mental health, and many experienced severe depression. The paper recommended that there should be no attempts to separate families, and appropriate mechanisms should be developed for the UKBA to take into account the views of children subject to enforcement action on all decisions which affect them. Also, all families should have access to good-quality publicly funded legal representation from an early stage in their claim
