AB  - The article focuses on asylum seekers and their right to be allowed to live in the community pending determination of their application for refugee status. The mandatory detention of people in jail-like centres demonstrates a lack of compassion for the suffering of other human beings but this article argues a number of propositions that go beyond the simple humanitarian argument. There are a number of economic, legal, ethical, political and social cohesion reasons why a government, keen to be seen by its populace and the international community as a humane liberal democracy, might wish to dismantle policies which insist that asylum seekers are subject to mandatory detention. Detaining asylum seekers, for other than short term processing, subjects them to psychological and physical harm, undermines our international reputation, and undermines the Australian economy. This is so because, in the short term, there is the cost of detention and the foregoing of the productive capacity of those detained. In the long term, the majority of asylum seekers are granted residence in Australia, but their productive capacity is reduced as a direct result of the trauma and missed training opportunities that occur as a result of their incarceration
