AB  - Global estimates suggest 20 million children from hundreds of different countries and cultures are currently displaced from their homes as refugees or internally displaced persons (USCR, 2000). Each year hundreds of thousands of children are resettled in second or third countries of asylum. However, little is known about children within asylum camps. With the explosion of asylum seekers worldwide, many being children, gaining insight into the development, well-being, and coping of children in asylum camps must be a primary concern of the international community. The goal of this research study was to augment understanding of the experiences of asylum seeking children in Gimo, Sweden. Twenty refugee children (11 males, 9 females) between 7 and 13 (M = 10.0 years) and their parents participated in the study and represented three linguistic groups. Eight (40%) of the participating children and parents spoke Bosnian, four (20%) Russian, and eight (40%) Arabic. The children and parents were presented with a battery of assessment instruments measuring the presence of trauma and its symptoms, socio-emotional behavior, and perceived social support. Parents and children also participated in an in-depth interview, and children's drawings about their experiences as refugees were collected. Analyses of the surveys documented the presence of traumatic life events and trauma symptoms in the sample, as well as socio-behavioral difficulties. A moderate amount of social support was perceived by children, although no relation between perceived social support and adjustment was detected in the participants as was a priori hypothesized. Significant differences on the survey measures as a function of linguistic group and length of time in the asylum camp were found. Several persistent themes recurred in the interviews. All children and parents expressed the presence of trauma and suffering, loss of humanity as a refugee, uncertainty, and the need of support and restoration of normalcy in their lives. This exploratory research was a first step into understanding the asylum setting for refugee children. More research must be conducted and asylum policies examined because further investigation and insight into the healthy development and psychosocial well-being of refugee children is an investment in our collective human future. 
