AB  - The paper analyzes Canada's practice of detaining a subset of the asylum seeker population pending a decision regarding their application for refugee status. The author argues that Canadian practices fall short of customary international standards in some respects, particularly as they relate to the co-mingling of detained asylum seekers with criminals. To support the analysis, a survey was administered to explore the attitudes and awareness of detention officers at a maximum-security correctional facility in British Columbia that holds a mixed population of persons awaiting sentence, persons on remand, and detained asylum seekers. The study is unique in that most research to date has studied the effects of detention on the person detained, rather than looking at those who exercise control over the detention environment. The findings support the conclusions that corrections officers are not generally aware of the unique circumstances of asylum seekers under their custody and that co-mingling should be avoided. The background of the paper covers the deleterious health effects of detention on asylum seekers and how the identity of an asylum seeker is constructed and framed so as to create a public perception of fear and mistrust. Specific reference is made to the role of the Canadian Red Cross in monitoring the conditions of detained asylum seekers, which is supplemented by a Field Guide for Canadian Red Cross delegates who conduct detention visits
