AB  - Detained immigrants may be especially vulnerable in terms of their health because of past and present circumstances, and may lack entitlements to care due to their legal situation. This exploratory mixed methods study aimed to test the usefulness of a questionnaire among former detainees in examining perceptions of their health needs and access to care in UK immigration detention (immigration removal centres). 30 former detainees completed questionnaires, and 27 of these also participated in semi-structured interviews, in June/July 2010; all had been released from detention in the past 12 months. The article describes the study methodology and presents the results, reporting on findings about pre-existing health issues, health issues in detention, access to health care services, and medication. The results showed that 66% of the participants entered detention with pre-existing mental or physical health conditions that required ongoing or new treatments, and that a variety of physical and mental health needs arose during detention. The phrasing and content of the questionnaire and interview guide were also tested and developed in preparation for an intended larger study. The authors conclude that access to health care in detention was often problematic in its effectiveness or availability, and that the results cast doubt on how appropriately the mental and physical health needs of detainees are provided for within the current UK detention estate
